04765nam a22006615i 9780520952102DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132013cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209521027 a10.1525/97805209521022doi  a(DE-B1597)519484  a(OCoLC)851157936  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aQL76.5.J32bM55 2014 7aHIS0030002bisacsh04a590.7352135223  aAK 17630qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/2536:19181 aMiller, Ian Jared, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Nature of the Beasts :bEmpire and Exhibition at the Tokyo Imperial Zoo /cIan Jared Miller. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (360 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAsia: Local Studies / Global Themes ;v2700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Transliteration -- tIntroduction: Japan’s Ecological Modernity -- tPart One. The Nature of Civilization -- tPart Two. The Culture of Total War -- tPart Three. After Empire -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is widely known that such Western institutions as the museum, the university, and the penitentiary shaped Japan’s emergence as a modern nation-state. Less commonly recognized is the role played by the distinctly hybrid institution—at once museum, laboratory, and prison—of the zoological garden. In this eye-opening study of Japan’s first modern zoo, Tokyo’s Ueno Imperial Zoological Gardens, opened in 1882, Ian Jared Miller offers a refreshingly unconventional narrative of Japan’s rapid modernization and changing relationship with the natural world. As the first zoological garden in the world not built under the sway of a Western imperial regime, the Ueno Zoo served not only as a staple attraction in the nation’s capital—an institutional marker of national accomplishment—but also as a site for the propagation of a new "natural" order that was scientifically verifiable and evolutionarily foreordained. As the Japanese empire grew, Ueno became one of the primary sites of imperialist spectacle, a microcosm of the empire that could be traveled in the course of a single day. The meaning of the zoo would change over the course of Imperial Japan’s unraveling and subsequent Allied occupation. Today it remains one of Japan’s most frequently visited places. But instead of empire in its classic political sense, it now bespeaks the ambivalent dominion of the human species over the natural environment, harkening back to its imperial roots even as it asks us to question our exploitation of the planet’s resources.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aImperialismxSocial aspectszJapanxHistoryy19th century. 0aNature and civilization -- Japan -- History. 0aNature and civilizationzJapanxHistory. 0aPhilosophy of nature -- Japan -- History. 0aPhilosophy of naturezJapanxHistory. 0aUeno Dobutsuen (Tokyo, Japan) -- History. 0aZoos -- Social aspects -- Japan -- History. 0aZoosxSocial aspectszJapanxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh1 aRitvo, Harriet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095210240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520952102423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520952102/original  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California 